message.content:
To align a row of divs to the right using Flexbox, you can use the `justify-content` property and set it to `flex-end`. Here's an example:

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
}

.divs {
  width: 100px;
  height: 50px;
  margin-right: 20px;
  background-color: #f0f0f0; /* for demonstration purposes only */
}

/* This is the key property to align the divs to the right */
.container {
  justify-content: flex-end;
}
```

```html
<div class="container">
  <div class="divs"></div>
  <div class="divs"></div>
  <div class="divs"></div>
</div>
```

In this example, the container has a `display` value of `flex`, which enables Flexbox. The `.divs` elements are children of the container and have been assigned widths and heights for demonstration purposes.

The magic happens in the CSS rule that targets the container. By setting `justify-content` to `flex-end`, we're telling the browser to align the divs to the end (right) of their parent container, while still allowing them to maintain their relative positions within the flow of the layout.

Note: If you want to justify content only for a specific row or column, you might need to adjust your HTML structure and target that specific element with your Flexbox properties.
